         NodeComment="Apply Orientation Warping (Strafe Warping is a better descriptor) to the motion matching output, which causes the feet to move in different directions based on the locomotion direction. This can allow a forward walk to \"strafe\" at different angles, which reduces foot sliding.\r\n\r\nCurrently there is an issue with orientation warping when the animation is not moving in a straight line, which is why we use an anim curve to only enable orientation warping during sections of the animations where the motion is straight, This should be fixed in future releases."

Begin Object Class=/Script/UnrealEd.EdGraphNode_Comment Name="EdGraphNode_Comment_1" ExportPath="/Script/UnrealEd.EdGraphNode_Comment'/Game/Blueprints/ABP_SandboxCharacter.ABP_SandboxCharacter:AnimGraph.EdGraphNode_Comment_1'"
   CommentColor=(R=0.300000,G=1.000000,B=0.300000,A=1.000000)
   bCommentBubbleVisible_InDetailsPanel=False
   NodePosX=-4016
   NodePosY=-1456
   NodeWidth=1024
   NodeHeight=1712
   bCommentBubblePinned=False
   bCommentBubbleVisible=False
   NodeComment="Motion Matching Node:\r\n\r\nThis node is the primary AnimGraph node that drives pose selection in a Motion Matching system.\r\n\r\nThe Motion Matching node requires two key components:\r\n\r\n1. A Pose Search Database, which contains the animation data the node will use to make selections. Additionally, Pose Search Database assets use a Pose Search Schema asset which defines what pose and trajectory data is used to make the selection.\r\n\r\n2. A Pose History node, which contains the pose and Character Trajectory data that will be used to query and match animation data against.\r\n\r\nIn this example setup, the Pose Search Database asset is set in the Update Motion Matching Function, which can be viewed in the nodes Details panel in the On Update property.\r\n\r\nIn addition to the required inputs, the node has some additional notable features.\r\n\r\nOn the Motion Matching node you can use the Blend Time float input to dynamically change the blend time. This can be helpful when different kinds of animations need to blend at different speeds. In this example setup, the Blend Time input is set using the Get_MMBlendTime function.\r\n\r\nThe Motion Matching node also has two AnimNode Functions that are applied to the node:\r\n\r\n1. On Update which calls the Update_MotionMatching function.\r\n\r\n2. On Motion Matching State Update which calls the Update_MotionMatching_PostSelection function.\r\n\r\nThe Update_MotionMatching function is evaluating a Chooser asset and outputs an array of Motion Matching Databases. This allows us to separate our locomotion data into multiple databases and allows the Chooser to filter the pool of animation data the Motion Matching node can search in any given frame, to only relevant animations. This implementation can increase both your control over the final selection and reduce your projects performance cost.\r\n\r\nThe Update_MotionMatching_PostSelection function allows us to perform additional logic based on the result of the Motion Matching selection. In this case, we cache the database the selected animation is in so that we can grab any tags it has, which can be used for future selection logic. The tags are grabbed in the event graph (due to a thread safety issue). See \"CurrentDatabaseTags\".\r\n\r\nYou can also double-click the Motion Matching Node to open up it\'s Blend Stack Graph, which is an internal graph applied to each animation where we\'re handling Orientation Warping and Steering."
   NodeGuid=BC454C054C6AFF6447BFFF8E7FACDD0B
End Object

Begin Object Class=/Script/UnrealEd.EdGraphNode_Comment Name="EdGraphNode_Comment_3" ExportPath="/Script/UnrealEd.EdGraphNode_Comment'/Game/Blueprints/ABP_SandboxCharacter.ABP_SandboxCharacter:AnimGraph.EdGraphNode_Comment_3'"

   NodePosY=-1408
   NodeWidth=480
   NodeHeight=1824
   bCommentBubblePinned=False
   bCommentBubbleVisible=False
   NodeComment="Offset Root Bone (Experimental!):\r\n\r\nThe Offset Root Bone node dynamically applies an offset to the characters root bone in order to keep the mesh more planted when capsule movement and animation data do not match.\r\n\r\nFor Translation, the root is allowed to deviate from the capsule within a fixed radius during locomotion, which is most noticeable during starts and pivots. When stopping, the offset will Release, or blend out, so that the character stays at the capsule center when idle.\r\n\r\nSee the Get_OffsetRootTranslationMode function for more information.\r\n\r\nFor Rotation, the root bone is allowed to rotate independently from the capsule, so that rotation is entirely controlled with root motion, which gets steered within the motion matching node to always align toward the target. This makes it easier to perform more complex rotational animations like turn in places, turn starts, and turn pivots.\r\n\r\nSee the Get_OffsetRootRotationMode function for more information.\r\n\r\nKnown Issues that will be fixed in future releases:\r\n\r\n-Translation offset has no collision checks, so it can clip into geometry.\r\n\r\n-When a montage plays, we release the offset, however the release in conjunction with motion warping in the montage might cause undesired movements.\r\n\r\n-How the offset is interpolated out is hardcoded at the moment.\r\n"
   NodeGuid=C90841BB4A6E97CCBE832881470E77B3
End Object

   NodeComment="Simple Aim Offset:\r\n\r\nThis Apply Mesh Space Additive node makes the character look toward the cameras facing direction when the camera and character are aligned within a set threshold. This threshold is defined in the Enable_AO function. The characters additive aiming poses are contained within a BlendSpace, which uses the Get_AOValue function to determine the axis based on the delta between the characters rotation and the camera rotation.\r\n\r\nThis example set up also uses a Dead Blending node, which is an advanced type of inertialization blend node that supports blend curves, and is used so that the Aim Offset can be reset when blending in without popping. This setup ensures the blend is always smooth, otherwise blending into the offset while is simultaneously blending out would cause blend issues."

            Begin Object Name="EdGraphNode_Comment_2" ExportPath="/Script/UnrealEd.EdGraphNode_Comment'/Game/Blueprints/ABP_SandboxCharacter.ABP_SandboxCharacter:AnimGraph.AnimGraphNode_StateMachine_1.State Controller.AnimStateTransitionNode_21.Transition.EdGraphNode_Comment_2'"
               bCommentBubbleVisible_InDetailsPanel=False
               NodePosX=-1360
               NodePosY=-640
               NodeWidth=1568
               NodeHeight=960
               bCommentBubblePinned=False
               bCommentBubbleVisible=False
               NodeComment="This transition handles the concept of \"breaking\" a rotational animation.\r\n\r\nSometimes, right after a start or a pivot is triggered, the Target Rotation changes rapidly on the following frames. For instance, say you perform a 90 degree pivot, but then quickly rotate the input further to perform a 180 (happens frequently on gamepad), or begin a forward start but then quickly rotate to the left or right. In these cases, we want to perform a reselction since the current anim is likely no longer a good choice.\r\n\r\nIn order to do this, we cache the value of the Target Rotation whenever a transition begins into a second rotator \"Target Rotation on Transition Start\" (set within the \"OnstateEntry\" anim node function). Then, on following frames we interpolate that rotator toward the Target Rotation in the \"OnUpdate\" anim node function. Becuase this value is interpolated, if the target rotation changes slowly, the delta between the two will stay small. But it is changes quickly enough, the delta will be large. Therefore, If the delta is greater than 60 degrees and we are still in the beginning of a start or pivot (we can know this by checking the current tags and the current state time), then we should trigger a reselection by restarting this state.\r\n\r\nThe \"sensitivity\" of the break can be tuned by modifying the interp speed as well as the angle threshold."
               NodeGuid=AD44E28E4F274BBA0413BDB137D9F5A3
            End Object
            MyResultNode="/Script/AnimGraph.AnimGraphNode_TransitionResult'AnimGraphNode_TransitionResult_0'"
            Schema="/Script/CoreUObject.Class'/Script/AnimGraph.AnimationTransitionSchema'"

Begin Object Class=/Script/UnrealEd.EdGraphNode_Comment Name="EdGraphNode_Comment_8" ExportPath="/Script/UnrealEd.EdGraphNode_Comment'/Game/Blueprints/ABP_SandboxCharacter.ABP_SandboxCharacter:AnimGraph.EdGraphNode_Comment_8'"
   CommentColor=(R=1.000000,G=0.833333,B=0.000000,A=1.000000)
   bCommentBubbleVisible_InDetailsPanel=False
   NodePosX=-4016
   NodePosY=288
   NodeWidth=1024
   NodeHeight=1024
   bCommentBubblePinned=False
   bCommentBubbleVisible=False
   NodeComment="State Machine + Choosers + Motion Matching + Blendstack (Experimental!):\r\n\r\nThis is a highly experimental setup that aims to combine the controllability of State Machines, the flexibility of Choosers, the power of Motion Matching, and the blending behavior of Blend Stack, all in an effort to build a scalable locomotion system that is artist friendly and easy to control.\r\n\r\nThe state machine below is used as purely a logical state machine, and outputs no pose. Its job is to write to the Blend Stack using state entry anim node functions. The Two Way Blend allows only the Blend Stack pose to pass through, but is set to \"always update children\", ensuring that the State Machine\'s logic can update before the Blend Stack.\r\n\r\nThe main purpose of this setup is to inform future tool development and experiment with workflow questions such as \"what could we do if state machines used a blend stack internally, and could easily handle state re-entry?\" Although the current workflow is far from ideal, we felt it\'d be great to show this off anyway."
   NodeGuid=A5E46E534F1DCD6AED25A2A30D0D34B4
End Object
